<HL>
   Taiwan's Export Orders Grow
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan -- Export orders for Taiwanese products in
May rose 2.6% to US$6 billion from the previous month and
represent growth of 4.5% from $5.74 billion in exports a year
earlier, the Economics Ministry said.
   Officials attributed the month-to-month rise to an
increase in orders for machinery and transportation
equipment. Orders for machinery totaled $580 million, up 27%
from the previous month. About 48% of the orders came from
Southeast Asian clients, followed by 21% from the U.S.
Transportation orders increased to $397 million in May from
$323 million in April.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Taiwan export orders from January through May amounted to
$27.73 billion, down 0.64% from a year earlier.
   The U.S. remained the leading destination for Taiwanese
exports, accounting for orders valued at $2.37 billion in
May, up 10% from April but down 0.63% from a year earlier.
</TEXT>
