<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Someday They'll Face the Barren Waste
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9
</SO>
<IN>
HOME CONSTRUCTION (HOM)
</IN>
<LP>
   In regard to William Fulton's May 8 editorial-page
article, "Can Anything Stop Los Angeles?": In 1983 I was
transplanted to the west end of the San Fernando Valley, and
I've witnessed an incredible metamorphosis of the area.
Development has been, shall we say, rampant.
   I believe there is a very affirmative yes to Mr. Fulton's
question as to whether the continued sprawling of Los Angeles
will ever cease. It has to do with one little precious
commodity called water.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Fulton correctly describes the economic effects of the
housing bonanzas in the valleys adjoining the San Fernando.
He aptly notes that areas such as Mojave and Rosamond are
next. But he and the developers are living in a fool's
paradise by failing to consider the impact these new projects
will make on available drinking water. It is a desert out
there and we are running out of water here.
   Los Angeles is finally catching up with its northern
cousins and moving to water rationing. Areas such as Santa
Barbara now have strict policies on water usage and
consumption. Reclaimed water is being used -- however, this
will surely not be enough for the demand required in these
newly developed areas.
   Los Angeles, the San Fernando Valley and most of Southern
California are going to have to face the music and ratchet
down the laissez-faire attitude toward unchecked development.
The leaders here have truly been living in La La Land with
regard to meeting basic human needs for open recreational
space. If the developers want to develop, then LA's
government leaders should be giving them incentives to
improve what is already here with more parks, a reliable mass
rail system and better drinking water. Los Angeles doesn't
need more condos, strip malls or freeways. It needs active
leadership.
   David Van Horn
   Woodland Hills, Calif.
   ---
   Mr. Fulton's article reveals how current public policies
are immeasurably cruel to the poor.
   Basic food is cheap -- five pounds of rice cost $2. Used
clothing is cheap in thrift shops. Many poor people can even
afford cheap used cars. But the cost of housing has been
artificially raised in many areas. This dreadful shortage of
housing is not an act of nature, like a shortage of rain, but
is the direct result of deliberate, purposeful zoning and
"growth restrictions." Once this is done, "subsidized
housing" is promoted as a sop to the poor.
   We forget that the best way to ensure a good supply of
cheap used cars for lower-income people is just to keep on
building cars. The same is true of housing. The poor never
lived in new housing or drove new cars -- they moved into the
houses that wealthier people moved out of when new housing
was built. While at one time suburbs were towns in their own
right, containing a cross section of people from rich to
poor, many such suburbs now are wealthy bedroom communities.
The governments of such communities are legally able to
restrict housing and push up the price of homes to $325,000.
But would we tolerate a policy of the middle classes and the
wealthy to restrict production of food and clothes, to push
up the price of rice to $5 a pound, the price of a shirt to
$100, just so more lower-income people could come to
"subsidized" thrift shops and soup kitchens?
   Zoning and growth restrictions should be abandoned; they
reflect the legal enforcement of the wishes of those who have
a place to live, not those who need a place to live. Local
governments should vigorously build roads, schools, parks and
public utilities to keep up with where people want to live --
not to restrict them.
   Will Chamberlain
   Needham, Mass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0139
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0139.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   K-Tron International
   Indicates It Expects
   Net to Rise This Year
   ----
   By Anne E. Nichols
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7B
</SO>
<CO>
   KTII
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
</IN>
<LP>
   PITMAN, N.J. -- K-Tron International Inc. is "comfortable"
with analysts' estimates of 1990 per-share earnings in the
area of $1.20, John C. Tucker, vice chairman and chief
financial officer, said.
   That would indicate net income of about $3.5 million. For
1989, the maker of gravimetric feeders, blenders and security
systems reported earnings of $3.2 million, or $1.08 a share,
on revenue of $57.6 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   K-Tron expects to post increased sales for the second
quarter, but profit will be "tighter" than a year ago because
of "a shifting mix in our product offering," said Leo Beebe,
chairman and chief executive officer, in an interview. He
didn't make a specific forecast. For the 1989 second quarter,
the company reported earnings of $1.1 million, or 36 cents a
share, on revenue of $14.9 million.
   K-Tron's gravimetric feeders and blenders are devices used
in controlling the rate at which ingredients are fed or mixed
in to make various products. The equipment is sold to
manufacturers of chemicals, plastics and food products.
K-Tron's gravimetric security systems are designed to detect
theft in retail stores by sensing changes in weight of
displayed merchandise.
   The order backlog for feeders and blenders, valued at
about $18 million, is 39% ahead of a year ago, said Mr.
Bebee. He also cited the 15% improvement in the
foreign-exchange rate as an encouraging sign for healthy 1990
earnings.
   In the 1990 first quarter, K-Tron opened a sales, service
and technology-training center in Singapore, hoping to
establish a stronger presence in the Far East and the Pacific
Rim. Near-term, the company expects some "offsets" against
earnings for start-up expenses of the Singapore operation.
"And that isn't cheap," said Mr. Beebe.
   Noting "some softening" in the U.S. market, he said
conditions are stronger in Europe, where demand is running
about 10% better than last year. Indeed, Mr. Beebe said
K-Tron is "having difficulty meeting demand" in Europe.
   During the first quarter, K-Tron reduced its debt about $2
million and continued to have "good positive cash flow," Mr.
Beebe said. As of March 31, long-term debt was $20.5 million.
He said the company plans to continue decreasing its debt.
   Although 1989 results were hurt by the company's
introduction of a new line of gravimetric blenders, Mr. Beebe
said he expects earnings to benefit from K-Tron's new modular
feeder line, introduced in the U.S. about two weeks ago.
   "Ultimately, the new modular feeder will provide K-Tron
with the bulk of its feeders business," said Mr. Beebe. He
expects the modular line to supplant the company's other
feeder lines in the near future.
   The modular equipment is designed so that components can
be shifted or interchanged, permitting quick cleaning and
ingredient conversion. This new flexibility cuts down on
production costs for manufacturers. Beebe said the new design
is a "natural evolution" in feeders.
   "We don't think we have a major competitor with the
modular," Mr. Beebe said. "No one else makes this product."
K-Tron is receiving orders for the modular line from many of
the same multinational customers it has developed in Europe.
   Separately, Mr. Beebe said K-Tron expects to renew its
current RJ Reynolds Tobacco contract to provide
"loss-in-weight" security systems to retailers of cigarettes.
He said the company is also "probing the market" for other
applications of the loss-in-weight technology, testing it
with merchandisers of expensive clothing, cosmetics and
liquor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0138
</DOCNO>
