<HL>
   Ferrofluidics to Take
   A Charge in Quarter
   Of Up to $15 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7B
</SO>
<CO>
   FERO
</CO>
<LP>
   NASHUA, N.H. -- Ferrofluidics Corp., a maker of seals and
dampers for computers, said its expects to take a charge of
as much as $15 million in its fourth quarter and year ending
June 30, related to writeoffs and a corporate restructuring.
   In fiscal 1989, the company earned $52,000, negligible in
per-share terms, on sales of $20.2 million. Fiscal 1989
fourth-quarter results weren't broken out separately. In the
fiscal 1990 first nine months, Ferrofluidics had a net loss
of $561,000, or 19 cents a share, on sales of $21.6 million.
The company declined to forecast results for the current
fiscal year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Ferrofluidics said the planned charge will result partly
from a loss from the sale of its AF Technologies Ltd. unit in
Britain, and write-downs of other assets, inventories and
patents, including some related to its ferrofluid film
bearing program. The company also said it will eliminate a
deferred-tax asset on its books, because of adoption of new
Financial Accounting Standards Board standard.
   Ronald Moskowitz, chief executive officer, said the
restructuring "is in the long-term best interests of the
company and its shareholders, and will result in a more
profitable company."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
