<HL>
   Law:
   Imelda Marcos Remains an Enigma
   As Trial Often Borders on the Bizarre
   ----
   By Wade Lambert
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6B
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<LP>
   The long-running racketeering trial of Imelda Marcos has
shed surprisingly little light on whether the former
Philippine first lady was directly involved in illegal
activities. But it has done much to feed the mystery that
surrounds her.
   Is she the fragile defendant who breaks down at the
witness table, unable to go on? Or is she the indefatigable
"Madame" who leads her entourage through shopping sprees at
tiny Philippine stores in New York? Is she the quiet, forlorn
widow in mourning -- or the entertainer who belts out
requests to shouts of "More] More]" at a party celebrating
what would have been her 36th anniversary?
</LP>
<TEXT>
   And, more to the point in the case, did she plunder the
Philippines of more than $200 million and illegally use the
money to buy up jewelry, art and real estate in the U.S.?
   Closing arguments in the trial will begin Monday, and the
often-bizarre case is expected to go to the jury around the
end of June.
   The federal prosecutors handling the case have presented,
through charts, documents and nearly 100 witnesses, a largely
circumstantial picture of alleged theft and fraud. But nobody
has testified that they saw Mrs. Marcos's hand in the cookie
jar.
   Instead, Philippine bank officials and people involved in
the real estate investments have said it was merely their
understanding that the purchases were done at Mrs. Marcos's
bidding. Prosecutors claim that Mrs. Marcos knew that the
money used in the purchases was stolen.
   Meanwhile, defense attorney Gerry Spence, a flamboyant
Wyomian whose Western-style dress and country-lawyer demeanor
have stood out in the Manhattan courtroom, has tried to show
that Mrs. Marcos knew little about the way the money was
being invested.
   Moreover, Mr. Spence has maintained that the source of the
Marcoses' wealth can easily be accounted for, not by theft,
but by Mr. Marcos's discovery of an extraordinary gold hoard
supposedly hidden in the Philippines by a Japanese general
during World War II.
   So far, the 11-week trial has been interrupted four times
by Mrs. Marcos's ailments. More recently, Judge John Keenan
recessed the trial for an early lunch last week when mention
of a purchase of Nautilus weight-lifting equipment for her
daughter Imee, allegedly with government money, sent Mrs.
Marcos's blood pressure soaring.
   "I'm so sorry," she told her attorneys, through tears, as
she went to her personal nurse, waiting with a stethoscope.
Benjamin Cassiday III, one of her attorneys, later explained:
"There they are, talking about her kid's Nautilus equipment,
and all that . . . and it's very upsetting to her."
   On trial with Mrs. Marcos is Adnan Khashoggi, accused of
helping her conceal ownership of the Manhattan real estate.
Mr. Khashoggi's lawyer, James Linn, conceded that his client
was in close contact with the Marcoses after they fled to the
U.S. in 1986. But Mr. Linn said the dealings had nothing to
do with real estate -- instead, he was trying to find a safe
port for a shipment of gold owned by Mr. Marcos, in return
for a share of it.
   Although Mr. Linn has poked fun at his client for falling
for what sounds like such an incredible story, it may not be
as absurd as it seems. During a New York visit, Philippine
Solicitor General Francisco Chaves said investigators believe
they have tracked down the ship, although the gold was
already unloaded. He said President Corazon Aquino's
government is now trying to find the gold, which it maintains
was stolen.
   Mrs. Marcos's comments and behavior have added to the
trial's bizarre side. Still in mourning for her husband,
Ferdinand, who died in September, Mrs. Marcos wears only
black clothes, simple jewelry and an unimpressive selection
of black shoes.
   "I am the center of the crucifixion," she reportedly said
to a group of Filipinos in the courtroom around Lent. On
another day, during a break after a former banker testified
that Mrs. Marcos summoned him into her bedroom to discuss
money, she laughed as she told two visitors in the gallery:
"He's going into my bedroom -- Ferdinand must be jealous as
hell]"
   In court, her attorney, Mr. Spence, has generated his own
controversy. The 61-year-old lawyer has clashed with Judge
Keenan regularly for asking improper questions of witnesses
and trying to introduce irrelevant issues. Mr. Spence has
become increasingly sensitive about reactions to his conduct.
After a reprimand from the judge, he met in chambers with
Judge Keenan and complained that people were laughing at him
"on the Aquino side of the courtroom." Mr. Spence, who wears
a rattlesnake-skin belt and western jackets -- but no suits
-- said the judge was giving the jury the impression that he
was "just a B.S. guy." The judge replied that he was taking
the matter too personally.
   Mrs. Marcos created a more private stir at a party marking
what would have been her 36th wedding anniversary. At the
surprise party, reported in a local Philippine newspaper's
gossip column, Mrs. Marcos was also given a letter from her
husband, Ferdinand. The card -- which read: "To Imelda,
beyond death, I love you, Andy," signed with his nickname --
was written before he died and was kept secret from Mrs.
Marcos.
   The main event, however, was a performance by Mrs. Marcos,
who took the microphone to sing "Feelings" and "Don't Fence
Me In."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0130
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0130.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Chemical Firms
   Are Still Facing
   Industry Slump
   ---
   Weak Commodity Prices
   Are Expected to Reduce
   Overall 2nd-Period Net
   ----
   By Randolph B. Smith
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CUE UK DOW DD MTC ACY EY APD
</CO>
<IN>
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<LP>
   The chemicals industry continues its downward cycle, with
weak commodity prices expected to reduce overall
second-quarter earnings 15% to 20% from a year ago. Earnings
have perked up slightly since the first quarter, aided by
seasonal improvements and prices stabilizing at lower levels.
But the industry slump is expected to continue for at least
two more quarters.
   The more-cyclical, commodity-chemical and plastics
companies will see declines in the 30% to 35% range because
selling prices have dropped precipitously from peak levels a
year ago. Companies in this group include Quantum Chemical
Corp., Union Carbide Corp. and Dow Chemical Co.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The trend for diversified and specialty chemical makers,
such as Du Pont Co. and Monsanto Corp., is generally flat for
the second quarter. However, earnings will vary widely from
10% up to 10% down, depending on the company's individual
product mix. Despite generally strong demand and pricing,
many companies were hurt by weakness in major economic
sectors, including agriculture, automobiles and construction.
In addition, demand for synthetic fibers was down.
   The biggest factor in the overall second-quarter decline
is the 20% drop in selling prices for commodity chemicals,
triggered by excess capacity. Yet prices were better than
expected because maintenance and weather-related problems
idled much of the new capacity added in 1989. Nontheless,
prices for ethylene and its derivatives, for example, dropped
30% to 23 cents a pound, from 33 cents a pound in the
year-ago quarter. Styrene-plastic prices fell 17% to 38 cents
a pound, from 46 cents.
   In the commodity group, Quantum Chemical is expected to
report the worst year-to-year comparison because of its
exposure to polyethylene, which represents 60% to 70% of
earnings. The company won't get the full benefit of the
restart of its Morris, Ill., plant and a recent polyethylene
price increase, says Charles LoCastro of Donaldson, Lufkin &amp;
Jenrette Securities Corp. He says equity earnings will be
affected by losses in a propane marketing joint-venture.
Several estimates range from break-even to $1 a share. A year
ago, the New York-based company had income from continuing
operations of $46 million, or $1.85 a share, on sales of
$672.5 million.
   Similarly, Union Carbide's earnings are likely to be cut
in half by soft selling prices for polyethylene and ethylene
glycol, a major product used in antifreeze. In addition,
Brazil's economic austerity program is likely to cut the
Danbury, Conn.-based concern's earnings about seven cents a
share, says Leonard Bogner of Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. Estimates range from about 60 cents to 70 cents a share.
A year ago, Carbide had net income of $186 million, or $1.33
a share, on sales of $2.28 billion.
   For Dow Chemical, demand is holding for chemicals and
plastics. But profits will be hurt by weak prices and auto
industry exposure, as well as market softness and plant
maintenance shutdowns in Europe. Estimates range from $1.85
to $2 a share. A year ago, the Midland, Mich.-based concern
earned $728 million, or $2.70 a share, on sales of $4.60
billion.
   In the diversified group, American Cyanamid Co. is
expected to be among the leaders, with a 10% to 15% gain. The
Lederle pharmaceutical unit, which accounts for half of the
company's profit, is expected to show a strong 20% profit
improvement. Poor weather reduced expected gains in
agricultural chemicals, causing some analysts to downgrade
estimates to a range of $1.30 to $1.35 a share. A year ago,
Wayne, N.J.-based Cyanamid earned a restated $107.1 million,
or $1.15 a share, on sales of $1.30 billion.
   For Du Pont, earnings are likely to be flat or down
slightly from peak levels in the year-ago second quarter.
Most business segments will be flat. But fibers will be down
modestly as a result of weak demand for apparel fibers, such
as polyester and orlon, says Paul Leming of Morgan Stanley &amp;
Co. With wet weather hurting agricultural chemical sales and
mining operations, estimates range from 95 cents to $1. A
year ago, Wilmington, Del.,-based DuPont earned $714 million,
or $1 a share, on sales of $9.28 billion.
   Several analysts say Monsanto earnings will be flat
because of weak demand for agricultural chemicals, which
account for 20% of the company's sales and nearly 40% of
profit. Wet weather delayed farm planting and reduced
acreage. The downturn in automobiles and housing should
slightly reduce chemical profit. The NutraSweet unit is
expected to do well and drugs will be modestly up. Estimates
range from $3.50 to $3.80. A year ago, St. Louis-based
Monsanto earned $241 million, or $3.54 a share, on sales of
$2.35 billion.
   Ethyl Corp. is expected to gain 10% to 25% with strong
positions in a variety of specialty chemicals. The company
will benefit from improved sales of olefins used in
polyethylene production, antiknock gasoline additives,
bromine and lubricant additives. Estimates range from 47
cents to 54 cents a share. A year earlier, the Richmond,
Va.-based company earned from continuing operations $51.0
million, or 42 cents a share, on sales of $602.6 million.
   For Air Products &amp; Chemicals Inc., earnings are expected
to be flat. Industrial gases are expected to grow 5% to 10%,
balancing a 20% downturn in chemicals. Several estimates
range from $1 to $1.08. A year ago, the Allentown, Pa.-based
concern earned $56.6 million, or $1.04 a share, on sales of
$669 million.
</TEXT>
