<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   The Revolution Goes South
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   AFRIC
</CO>
<LP>
   Another socialist politburo has suffered a major setback
at the polls. This time the victor is not a charismatic labor
leader or a tousle-haired playwright but rather Islamic
fundamentalists. And so the world now sits up and wonders if
Algeria is about to become another Iran.
   Algeria need not devolve in that fashion. The unexpected
success of the Islamic Salvation Front in the municipal and
provincial elections last week signifies more about the
post-colonial past than it does about some fundamentalist
future.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Arabs have a saying that "the state eats the green and
the dry." They mean that an authoritarian government consumes
everything in its path. It captures the labor unions, the
guilds, the bar and the middle classes. It allows no
bourgeois opposition and renders exiled political leaders
almost powerless by strangling their domestic support. There
is only one refuge, the church. This has been the pattern in
Algeria.
   These are the first elections the post-colonial Algerian
government has permitted. While stifling dissent, the rulers
created a rich and corrupt apparatchik class. Meanwhile, oil
wealth was squandered on huge industrial public works, farms
were collectivized, the currency inflated and the young
denied opportunity (in sum, a familiar Third World scenario).
   Inevitably, opposition to the government flocked around
Islam, as opponents to communism in Poland flocked around the
Catholic church.
   Also, the Algerian population is overwhelmingly young, and
concentrated in urban centers along the coast. Unemployment
has been as high as 22% nationwide and 50% among the urban
poor. Throughout the Islamic crescent these idle young have
been the breeding ground for fundamentalist revolution. The
half educated young urban poor are nurtured by the welfare
organization that fundamentalists sponsor.
   But one of the peculiarities of Algeria is that while the
opposition is hostile to the legacy of socialist misrule, it
is not mainly composed of radical anti-moderns. Nor do most
supporters of the opposition despise the West or their
current president, Chadli Bendjedid. Indeed, President Chadli
is credited for having begun to open up his nation's
political system, and for allowing this election. Many of
those who voted for the fundamentalists would support a
secular opposition if one existed.
   The proper course now would be to throw the political
doors wide open. The Algerian government should allow an
array of non-fundamentalist opposition parties, and reduce
the danger of an Islamic revolution. The worst course would
be measures to stifle dissent.
   Too many Western commentators develop brain lock-up when
confronted by Islamic fundamentalism. Rather than being
imprisoned by the experience of Iran, the world might better
view these election results as an Eastern European democratic
revolution stuck in an Arab context. It even comes complete
with a reassertion of ethnic, in this case Berber, identity.
If real reform continues, the election results aren't likely
to lead to an Islamic revolution, or a wave of chaos and
emigration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0113
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0113.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Late-Day Rally Pulls Market Higher;
   MCI Communications Continues to Slide
   ----
   By Anne Newman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Over-the-counter stocks crawled marginally higher in the
last hour of trading after drifting most of the day.
   The Nasdaq Composite Index climbed 0.47 to 461.27, or
0.10%, as volume slipped slightly to 144.3 million shares
from 148.1 million Wednesday. Advancing shares beat
decliners, 963 to 916.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Institutional investors continued to step in and buy
stocks when they fell to attractive prices, said Ralph
Costanza, head of OTC trading at Smith Barney, Harris Upham.
"When they see an opportunity, they step in and buy," said
Mr. Costanza.
   The Nasdaq Composite Index opened lower and drifted 1.44
before recovering. Buying among smaller investors also is
orderly and cautious, he said. Small investors appear to be
buying shares of companies researched by brokerage firms
rather than chasing after speculative stories, according to
Mr. Costanza.
   Subaru of America was the day's most active issue, mainly
because Cantor Fitzgerald traded two blocks of more than 2
million shares each for buyers and sellers.
   Fuji Heavy Industries Ltd. of Japan is in a pact to buy
the 50.4% of Subaru it doesn't already own. Subaru rose 1/16
to 8 1/4 on 5.8 million shares.
   Telecredit tumbled 2 1/2 to 50 3/4 after the Los Angeles
provider of payment services said it agreed to be acquired by
Equifax, an Atlanta business-services concern. The agreement
calls for a stock swap valued at about $580 million. An
arbitrager at one large New York brokerage said the stock
stumbled because some investors think the proposed
combination may attract antitrust scrutiny. He added some
speculators had hoped Telecredit would be acquired in cash by
a larger, international finance or data-processing firm.
   MCI Communications, the day's second-most active stock,
continued to drift, slipping 5/8 to 41 on 3.5 million shares.
Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette telecommunications analyst Joel
Gross said in an interview that shares of the Washington,
D.C., long-distance carrier reacted to a new American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph tariff regulation that gives AT&amp;T more
flexibility in competitive pricing. The regulation became
effective by default after the Federal Communications
Commission failed to act on the proposed tariff within a
mandated time. However, Mr. Gross said he expects federal
regulators to eventually rule against the new regulation.
   MCI shares also have been pressured by the pending release
of FCC market-share data, which may show AT&amp;T's market share
rising a bit. Mr. Gross added, however, that when the data is
revised it will show that AT&amp;T's market share is continuing
to decline. He continues to rate MCI a "buy."
   Apple Computer added 1 7/8 to 41 7/8 on more than 1.9
million shares, leading the technology group. Shares of the
Cupertino, Calif., computer maker apparently got a boost from
a market survey showing that the dollar value of the
company's sales in May rose 50% from the year-earlier level
and that its share of the domestic personal-computer market
rose in May from a year earlier, according to Dow Jones
Professional Investor Report.
   Westmark International leaped 2 1/2 to 39 1/2 after the
Seattle medical-equipment maker said late Wednesday that
earnings for the second quarter ending June 30 will fall at
the low end of an estimated range of 45 to 50 cents a share,
up from 39 cents a share a year earlier. The stock recently
had weakened amid some analysts' concerns the earnings
wouldn't meet that range.
   Henley Properties added 3/4 to 6 3/4 after the Hampton,
N.H., real estate development company said it expects net
income for the second quarter ending June 30 to be about $80
million, up from $4.8 million on a pro forma basis a year
earlier. Henley also said it will sell its interests in two
trash-to-energy facilities for $10 million to Wheelabrator
Technologies Inc. That will enable Henley to reverse about
$100 million of deferred income currently included as a
liability on its financial statements and increase
shareholders' equity by that amount, the company added.
   LDDS Communications jumped 2 3/4 to 24, a new 52-week
high, apparently after Prudential-Bache analyst Charles
Nichols initiated coverage of the Jackson, Miss., provider of
long-distance telecommunications services with a "buy"
opinion, DJPIR reported.
   General Binding lost 2 1/2 to 18 1/2 after the Northbrook,
Ill., maker of business machines and supplies said it expects
second-quarter earnings will fall to 30 or 31 cents a share
from 35 cents a year earlier because of weaker markets and
higher expenses. That's below analysts' expectations of 38
cents a share.
   National Media slid 1/2 to 10 1/4 after the Philadelphia
provider of direct-marketing services reported fourth quarter
net income of 58 cents a share compared with a loss of six
cents a year earlier, adjusted for a 5% stock dividend paid
at year end. National Media also said it's "actively
investigating" the acquisition of telemarketing and "direct
response" companies.
   Drexler Technology skidded 1 15/16 to 1 5/16 after the
Mountain View, Calif., maker of optical data products said
late Wednesday that it's been unsuccessful in selling its
future license royalty payments and part of a full ownership
in its optical memory card manufacturing operation.
   Consequently, the company said its accountants expect to
issue a qualified financial report on the company for the
year ended March 31. Drexler said its cash is adequate to
fund operations for eight weeks without cash infusions of any
kind and it plans to cut executive salaries and furlough some
employees.
   Earth Technology dropped 1 to 7 5/8 after the
environmental consulting services company said fourth-quarter
earnings could be hurt if a weak backlog for its asbestos
consulting and laboratory services persists because of
project delays. The company also reported net income for the
third quarter ended May 25 of six cents a share, up from one
cent a year earlier.
   ---
   Craig S. Smith contributed to this column.
</TEXT>
