<HL>
   Defense in Chicago Futures Trial Blames
   `Ambiguous' Trading Rules, Assails U.S.
   ----
   By Scott McMurray
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C14
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   CHICAGO -- A defense attorney blamed "ambiguous" trading
rules for any alleged problems in this city's futures trading
pits and criticized the government for singling out three
futures traders for prosecution under those rules.
   If federal prosecutors don't like the way futures trading
is conducted, "let them change the damn rules; don't put Bob
Mosky in jail because of it," said Elliot Samuels, an
attorney for Robert Mosky, one of three Swiss franc futures
traders charged with fraud who are on trial here in federal
court.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Defense attorneys for all three traders also maintained
that futures trading is so complex and hectic that the
undercover federal agent who posed as a trader in 1988
regularly bumbled his own trades and frequently misunderstood
what was going on around him.
   They also attempted to raise questions in the jurors'
minds about the integrity of the agent, Randall Jannett,
saying he appeared to ignore evidence that the three accused
traders had abided by the rules of their profession. The
attorneys made their comments in closing arguments to the
jury in the seven-week trial.
   Prosecutors argued that the defendants repeatedly stole
from customers to avoid costly trading errors and to pad
their incomes. Fraudulent trading in the Swiss franc pit by
the defendants was "systematic and longstanding," said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Daniel Gillogly.
   Mr. Mosky and the other two traders, Danny Scheck and
David Zatz, were indicted last year for allegedly stealing
from futures trading customers in the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange's Swiss franc futures trading pit.
   Forty-five other individuals also were indicted last year
as a result of a federal undercover investigation of futures
trading at the Merc and the Chicago Board of Trade. The three
Swiss franc futures traders are the first of the indicted
traders to go on trial.
   The central issue of the trial is the "open outcry" rule,
which requires that all futures trades be made "openly and
competitively" in an exchange trading pit, Mr. Samuels said.
But the lack of a concise definition for this rule has left
the defendants open to prosecution for following pit customs
and practices that allow traders to survive in the frantic
trading atmosphere, he said.
   Throughout the trial the defense attorneys hammered away
at Mr. Jannett's repeated claims that he observed and at
times covertly tape-recorded the defendants making
non-competitive trades. They also assailed as unreliable
evidence given by two traders who earlier pleaded guilty to
reduced fraud charges in return for providing evidence
against the three accused traders.
   The defense attorneys maintained that many of those
alleged non-competitive trades were actually two traders
confirming the details of trades made earlier that the agent
had failed to notice or record. Other examples of alleged
illegality were instances of traders resolving errors by
following pit practice of so-called local or independent
traders, resolving errors in favor of brokers who handle
customer orders, the attorneys said.
   The government contends that locals were passed
non-competitive winning trades to compensate for absorbing
such losses from brokers.
   Commodity regulations are "vague rules subject to
different interpretations," Mr. Samuels said. "This is life
in the pits. It's not pleasant, it's not serene, its not
pretty, but things get done."
   To try to underscore their argument that futures trading
is a frenetically paced business and difficult for outsiders
to comprehend, the defense attorneys offered a 20-minute
videotape of trading in the Swiss franc pit as their sole
defense. The unnarrated tape showed numerous examples of
traders leaping over each other to complete transactions and
frantically sorting through piles of orders.
   "The very complexity of the issues raised in this case
raises a reasonable doubt all by itself" as to the guilt of
the defendants, said Alan Blumenthal, Mr. Zatz's attorney.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney James Fleissner described such an
argument as a "Wizard of Oz" defense. It suggests "mere
mortals" such as federal agents or jurors will never be able
to understand the workings of a futures pit, he said. Accept
that, he told the jury, and "being a member of the Merc means
you can never be convicted" of fraudulent trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0102
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0102.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Is El Presidente
   A `Mufa,' a Bearer
   Of Very Bad Luck?
   ---
   Argentina's Leader Is Linked
   To Mayhem and Mishap;
   He Says He Isn't Cursed
   ----
   By Thomas Kamm
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<LP>
   BUENOS AIRES -- President Bush is going to do something
extraordinarily brave on Sept. 19. He is going to sit down in
the same room with Argentina's president, Carlos Menem.
   Whoops] Sorry. Don't say that word. Make it "Mendez," as
many Argentines do. Or be vaguer still. "El Presidente" will
do. "Just don't call him by his name," warns publishing
executive Carlos Ferrando. "It brings bad luck."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   And if just uttering the name is dangerous, imagine the
peril of actually being in the man's presence. Ask tennis
star Gabriela Sabatini or speedboat racer Daniel Scioli, both
of whom have been touched by the supposed Menem curse. "That
man," says taxi driver Cesar Rojas, artfully avoiding the
obvious trap, "has bad vibes. All he has to do is go
somewhere, and terrible things happen."
   In superstitious Argentina, such a man is a "mufa," a
cursed individual, and Mr. Menem's mufa-ness, having become
legend (and a joke), is also a political liability.
   "Menem's bad luck" is the cover story of last week's issue
of newsweekly "Noticias." And Humor, the satirical biweekly,
ran a cover story just before the soccer games of the World
Cup began. "If we want to win," the magazine advised, "he
shouldn't go to the `Mundial.'"
   The sports-loving Mr. Menem ignored Humor's advice and
flew to Italy to attend Argentina's opening match with
Cameroon. "I know people think I'm a mufa," he told an
Argentine radio station hours before the game. "But, today,
we'll show them it's not true. Today, this streak will end."
   Famous last words. Cameroon, a 500-to-one shot, beat
Argentina, the defending world champion, 1-0. Humor felt
vindicated. The pro-Communist daily "Sur" was no more
charitable. It attributed the loss to: "the Mendez effect."
Argentina might have done better had Ramon Diaz been playing.
But just days after Mr. Menem had publicly suggested that Mr.
Diaz be included on the Argentine squad, he hurt himself and
was out of action for six weeks. Of course, once el
Presidente had gone home, Argentina defeated the Soviet Union
and tied Romania, so it squeaked through to the second round,
fortunately without Mr. Menem in the cheering section.
   Argentina's soccer loss is but the latest in a string of
events that have won Mr. Menem his reputation as a mufa.
Updating the list of mufa-related mishaps, some of them quite
tragic, has become a national pastime.
   Some posited examples?
   Last July, Mr. Menem played a soccer game with Argentina's
national team, following which the team failed to win a game
for months. Sergio Batista, who sat out the game so Mr. Menem
could play, saw his $1 million contract to compete for an
Italian team fall through.
   Switching to tennis, Mr. Menem played a benefit game with
Gabriela Sabatini. Shortly thereafter, Ms. Sabatini,
Argentina's No. 1 woman player, twisted her knee and was
idled for weeks.
   In September, el Presidente went for a boat ride with
outboard racer Daniel Scioli. The next day Mr. Scioli lost an
arm in an accident.
   To take his mind off Argentina's economic woes, Mr. Menem
went to the races. In the following week, four jockeys were
injured.
   Having passed like a tornado through the sports world, Mr.
Menem piloted an Argentine Pucara jet. Bad for business. A
few days later, Brazil rescinded a contract to buy 30 of the
planes.
   Mr. Menem named Miguel Roig to be his economics minister.
Five days later, the businessman had a heart attack and died.
A few weeks later, Julio Corzo, the minister of health and
social action and the president's closest friend, was killed
in a plane crash.
   Tango singer Hugo del Carril was recovering in a Buenos
Aires hospital from a cardiovascular illness. Mr. Menem paid
a visit and, two hours later, Mr. del Carril was dead.
   Days after Mr. Menem went to the Olmos penitentiary to
inaugurate modernization work, 33 inmates died in a blaze.
   Just as he was about to board his plane to Kuala Lumpur
earlier this month, a truck carrying a crane crashed into the
aircraft.
   Must more evidence be adduced? Taxi driver Carlos
Brachetti thinks not. "I hate to believe this stuff," he
says. "But one has to face facts: The man is a mufa."
   Mr. Menem, of course, doesn't buy the line. Pressed by
reporters upon his return from his ill-fated trip to Italy
about the bad luck he seems to sow like Johnny Appleseed, an
irascible Mr. Menem said all this mufa talk is "sheer
nonsense."
   He certainly didn't assume blame for Argentina's loss to
Cameroon. "I wasn't on the playing field," he said, adding
that no one blames Mikhail Gorbachev because Romania beat the
Soviet Union. "Argentina was never as lucky as {it has been}
under this government," he said.
   With the nation in deep economic crisis, many Argentines
can't quite fathom that claim. But there is a rough consensus
that Mr. Menem has been a source of amusement.
   Mufas, they say, bring bad luck to others but lead charmed
lives themselves. Mr. Menem's own luck hasn't been all that
terrific lately. He might wish to point that out next time
someone says he's a mufa. Mr. Menem's personal life has been
in considerable disarray. The reason: what Argentines call
"la crisis matrimonial," a domestic battle royal between Mr.
Menem and his wife of 23 years, Zulema.
   The two have been on the outs, on and off, for years but
were reconciled in 1988 during the presidential campaign. No
sooner had Mr. Menem assumed the presidency, however, than
the spats resumed -- more this time over politics than over
Mr. Menem's alleged philandering, which had been an issue.
Mr. Menem, a lip-service Peronist, clashed with his wife, who
is more orthodox. She, who consorts with her husband's
critics, said Mr. Menem's entourage is corrupt. "She is my
biggest opponent," Mr. Menem grumbled.
   Mrs. Menem moved out of the president's official
residence, saying that the phones were bugged. She moved back
in, then he moved out. He slept at the office or at the homes
of friends. She denied him access to his sash and scepter.
   Unable to persuade his wife to leave the Quinta de Olivos,
the 59-year-old Mr. Menem issued a decree ordering her to go.
She came home one day to find that she had been locked out.
   "Corruption is taking hold of the country," she said.
"This is much more than the breakup of a marriage, this is a
political problem."
   Mr. Menem has handled the matter rather more firmly than
he has handled hyperinflation, and public opinion seems to
respect his actions vis-a-vis Zulema. But does that mean he
isn't a mufa? Hardly. It proves only that he's no luckier in
love than he is on the soccer field or in the cockpit. And
some Argentines, unamused by any of this, don't just refuse
to utter his name, they don't want to talk about the Menems'
cat fight at all.
   And he, known for flamboyance, is for once lying low.
Courting the danger of meeting up with Mr. Menem, this
reporter out of a sense of professional duty and diligence
requested an interview for this story. Much to his relief, he
got no reply.
</TEXT>
