<HL>
   Phone Firms
   Ordered to Cut
   Access Rates
   ---
   FCC Tells Local Companies
   To Lower by $1.1 Billion
   Fees in Next 12 Months
   ----
   By Mary Lu Carnevale
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   NYN SBC USW AIT PAC BEL BLS MCIC T UT
</CO>
<IN>
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL COMMUNICATIONS COMMISSION (FCC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Federal Communications Commission
ordered the nation's local telephone companies to cut the
access rates charged to long-distance companies by $1.1
billion, a move that will give consumers a break on their
long-distance bills.
   The reductions in the year starting July 1 -- $696 million
more than the local companies proposed in April -- apply to
the rates that long-distance companies pay for the
origination and termination of interstate phone calls. The
FCC estimates that interstate-access revenues total about $19
billion annually.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   An American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. spokesman said the
company is studying the FCC order and plans to expand the
$160 million in rate cuts scheduled to take effect July 1. He
said it was too early to say how much of a savings customers
will see, but emphasized that "this means more reductions for
consumers and small businesses."
   Spokesmen for MCI Communications Corp. and United
Telecommunications Inc.'s US Sprint Communications unit said
their companies would remain competitive with AT&amp;T. In the
past, most access-charge reductions have been passed along to
long-distance customers.
   The FCC said its common carrier bureau found that
inaccurate projections of demand and costs would result in
excessive returns for local phone companies. The agency
figured that by underestimating the likely demand for
service, the local companies would have collected $105
million more than they should have.
   The bureau slashed more than $289 million in access costs
after finding that many local phone companies forecast
"unusually high growth rates in their costs without providing
adequate explanation or justification." It said it cut an
additional $302 million for other inflated costs. Further,
the agency said that some phone companies made exorbitant
forecasts of depreciation expense.
   In an interesting twist, the commission found that several
Bell companies had misallocated lobbying expenses to
operating-expense accounts in 1989, wrongly passing on
several million dollars of lobbying costs to phone-company
customers. The agency cited Ameritech, BellSouth Corp., Nynex
Corp. Pacific Telesis Group and Southwestern Bell Corp. The
agency said that although the Baby Bells "are entitled to
engage in lobbying, the commission's rules make clear that
associated expenses must be excluded from rate-making."
   Don Evans, MCI's director-technical regulatory affairs,
said, "We're excited that the FCC investigated lobbying
expenses, but I hope this isn't the end of it," he said.
"This is only the interstate part and only what local
exchange carriers admitted to."
   MCI had asked the FCC to investigate whether the Bell
companies were lobbying Congress at customers' expense.
Washington-based MCI made its request earlier this year after
the Bells earmarked $21 million -- $3 million apiece -- for
an enormous campaign to persuade Congress to ease
restrictions in the consent decree that broke up the Bell
System. The decree bars the Baby Bells from providing the
content of information services, manufacturing
telecommunications gear and providing long-distance service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0093
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0093.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bell Atlantic Sees New Zealand Interest
   As Base for Expanding Pacific Business
   ----
   By Pamela J. Podger
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3D
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST BEL AIT
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
</IN>
<LP>
   PHILADELPHIA -- Bell Atlantic Corp. views its joint
acquisition with Ameritech of New Zealand's Telecom Corp. as
a base for expanding operations in the Pacific, said Raymond
W. Smith, Bell's chairman and chief executive officer
   Mr. Smith characterized the $2.5 billion purchase as "a
very important strategic move for us." Noting the economic
vitality of the Pacific Rim region, he said Bell Atlantic is
exploring possible business opportunities in such countries
as South Korea, Taiwan, Malaysia, Indonesia, Singapore and
Australia.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In an interview, Mr. Smith also indicated that the New
Zealand telephone operation, which already has a mostly
digital network, could become a hub for providing corporate
telecommunications services to the region. He noted that New
Zealand makes an attractive base for many reasons, including
its location in the region, its stable democratic government
and its English-speaking population.
   This week, Bell Atlantic and Ameritech filed court papers
seeking a waiver from U.S. District Judge Harold Greene to
permit the two Bell companies, as owners of New Zealand's
Telecom, to retain their interest in long-distance phone
traffic between New Zealand and the U.S.
   Hyde Tucker, president of Bell Atlantic's international
unit, said that, without such a waiver, New Zealand's
long-distance phone circuits will have to be reorganized at a
cost of as much as $10 million. He expressed hope that Judge
Greene would respond to the request quickly.
   Armed with about $550 million in available cash at the end
of the first quarter, Bell Atlantic has been on an
international shopping spree. This month, for example, the
company has teamed up with US West Inc. of Denver; the two
have been selected to build a cellular telephone system and a
public data network in Czechoslovakia.
   Bell Atlantic's Mr. Smith said business opportunities for
the company in the Pacific Rim area could range from
consulting and operating-system contracts to acquiring part
or all of country phone systems that may be privatized. He
declined to identify specific targets or disclose the
progress of any ongoing talks. But he noted that Bell
Atlantic recently signed a "memorandum of understanding" with
the government of South Korea regarding possible joint
ventures.
   Mr. Smith also acknowledged that Bell Atlantic's recent
successes in landing the New Zealand and Czech business
ventures have the effect of reducing the likelihood that his
company would also take on the purchase of another large
national telephone system, such as those of Mexico and
Argentina.
   Peter Troughton, who will remain Telecom's managing
director and chief executive, said the New Zealand company's
total work force has been slashed recently to about 16,000
employees from a peak level of about 26,500. He predicted
that the total would be reduced to about 12,000 over the next
two years.
   For the fiscal year ended March 31, Telecom earned $148
million on revenue of about $1.3 billion. Profits were
reduced by heavy capital spending on network improvements.
   Mr. Troughton didn't make any predictions about how
profitable Telecom could become, but he said he doesn't see
why it should be "any less profitable" than the regional Bell
companies, including Ameritech and Bell Atlantic.
   Until the late 1980s, New Zealand's telephone company was
government-owned, heavily regulated and generally regarded as
a poor performer in responding to consumer needs. For
example, the network frequently "crashed" and went dead in
the middle of a business day because network capacity was
inadequate. Moreover, customers typically waited up to eight
minutes for a dial tone, and about 50% of
directory-assistance queries weren't answered correctly.
   But many improvements have been made in the past two
years. Indeed, the agreement last week to sell Telecom to
Ameritech, Bell Atlantic and two New Zealand companies
represents a sustained effort by the government to address
such market needs by taking the phone system private.
   Mr. Troughton noted that the company has realized strong
growth in demand for telephone services, since rates on toll
calls were cut 50% and international-call prices were also
reduced substantially.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
