<HL>
   Earth Technology
   Reports Strong Rise
   In Quarterly Profit
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7A
</SO>
<CO>
   ETCO
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. -- Earth Technology Corp. reported
sharply higher results for the fiscal third quarter and nine
months, but cautioned that a slowdown in part of its business
may "slightly" affect fourth-quarter results.
   Jack J. Schoustra, chairman and chief executive, said he
is "comfortable" with earnings projections of about 50 cents
a share for the current fiscal year, which ends Aug. 25.
Earth Technologies is involved in waste management consulting
and specialized analysis of potential industrial sites.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the third quarter ended May 25, net income totaled
$190,000, or six cents a share, more than five times the
$33,000, or one cent a share, posted in the year-earlier
quarter. Revenue jumped 62% to $14.5 million from $9 million
on the strength of both acquisitions and growth of existing
business.
   Mr. Schoustra said the sharp earnings increase was due
mainly to depressed results in the year-earlier quarter,
stemming from an office closure and relocation. Moreover, he
said the latest period included "well in excess of $100,000"
of preparation and proposal costs for two, multiyear Air
Force contracts awarded during the period totaling $97
million.
   The executive said recent softening in backlog for
asbestos consulting and laboratory services might lower
fourth-quarter profit by "a cent or two." He said the problem
was a "hole" in an otherwise busy asbestos-removal work
schedule.
   For the fiscal nine months, Earth Technology had net
income of $1 million, or 32 cents a share, more than double
the $456,000, or 16 cents a share, in the year-earlier period
on fewer shares. Revenue rose 49% to $40.3 million from $26.9
million. Included in the latest period was about $100,000 of
"non-operating" costs related to a restated loss by a
subsidiary and a valuation change in deferred compensation
related to an acquisition.
   Mr. Schoustra said the company "never said it was
comfortable with one analyst's forecast that net income will
total about 55 cents a share this fiscal year" and that it
was "more comfortable" with an estimate of about 50 cents.
The executive said possible softening in the fourth quarter
might mean a drop of one or two cents from that 50-cent
figure.
   In the fiscal year ended Aug. 25, 1989, Earth Technology
had net income of $518,000, or 18 cents a share, on revenue
of $37.8 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
