<HL>
   Japan, Switzerland and U.S. Are Said
   To Have Most-Competitive Economies
   ----
   By Tim Carrington
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST JAPAN EUROP LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Japan, Switzerland and the U.S. ranked as the
world's three most-competitive economies, according to an
annual study by the World Economic Forum and the
International Institute for Management Development.
   The study, based on more than 300 criteria ranging from
tax structures to levels of social alienation, attempts to
rate countries according to how conducive they are to running
successful businesses. The study also included the subjective
but important measure of how much confidence business
executives had in the nations where they did business. Here,
West Germany, which placed fourth in the overall scoreboard,
ranked first -- apparently because of enthusiasm generated by
pending reunification with East Germany and investment plans
elsewhere in Eastern Europe.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The survey compiled a separate roster for economies that
have recently industrialized. In this group, the top three
were Singapore, Taiwan and Hong Kong.
   Growth expectations appear to be the strongest in Asia,
with South Korea leading the category of "rising stars."
Another contender in this group was Ireland, which won high
scores for expected industrial growth. According to the
survey's authors, Ireland "is developing a Far Eastern
country profile, which is reflected in the optimism of Irish
entrepreneurs."
   The survey's competitiveness rankings don't reflect the
difficulties international companies have breaking into
particular markets. Japan, which held the No. 1 ranking, is
considered one of the least-hospitable nations for foreign
corporations to invest in. The prominent position extended
Switzerland, where both the report's sponsors are based,
reflected the favorable tax policies there, along with
political stability.
   The U.S. ranked first for its human resources, a category
that includes the age, skills and size of the work force. The
survey also showed that in 1986, 59% of U.S.
20-to-24-year-olds were enrolled in some form of higher
education. Ranking relatively low in this survey was Britain,
where only 22% of this age group took part in higher
education.
   However, the U.S. came in sixth place in "future
orientation." In this category, which covers such items as
research funding and patents, Japan took first place.
   In worker productivity, Sweden and Singapore claimed the
highest ranking, with Japan coming in second place, and the
U.S. placing third. Germany took fifth place in the
productivity rankings, France seventh and Italy ninth. Of the
seven major industrial countries, Britain showed the lowest
worker productivity: It ranked 16th of the 34 countries
included in the survey.
   The study added several new categories this year. One was
a ranking of 23 countries according to how effectively they
prevented corruption. Here, Denmark and Singapore tied for
first place, while Italy came in 23rd. The U.S. fell close to
the middle, holding down the 13th place.
   While the report said that national economic competition
is a reality, it warned that "obsessive" rivalry between the
U.S., Japan, and Europe would be destructive. This "triad,"
the report said, controls about 60% of the world's gross
national product, with only 15% of its population. Trade wars
could leave the rest of the world in the cold, it warned.
However, the report predicted that over time, such nations as
Mexico, India, Brazil and China would gather greater economic
clout.
   Among the Eastern European nations, East Germany stands
the greatest chance for a successful transformation, the
study said, because of "the massive resource transfer" from
West Germany. The report gave Czechoslovakia and Hungary the
next best prospects. Poland got a gloomier review. "Having
the most tattered economy and being battered by a huge
foreign-debt burden, Poland's problem will be to ensure sheer
survival," the report said.
   In a discussion of Japan's success, the report emphasized
the nation's persistence. It noted that, in the Japanese
view, Western business executives expect "too much too soon."
Contentment -- or perhaps complacency -- is slower coming in
Japan. The study cited a Japanese survey that found that 52%
of the new generation of Tokyo residents believed they were
living in an affluent society, compared with 70% of a like
group living in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0068
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0068.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Short Interest
   Rose to Highs
   In Latest Month
   ---
   Big Board Figure Up 2.6%
   And Amex Climbed 0.3%
   In Period Ended June 15
   ----
   By Robert Daniels
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<IN>
SHORT SALES AND SHORT INTEREST (SHO)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Short interest reached record levels for the
month ended June 15, rising 2.6% on the New York Stock
Exchange and inching up 0.3% on the American Stock Exchange.
   For the first time in 15 months, Texas Air Corp. was
supplanted as the leading short-interest issue on the Amex,
as short volume in the Houston airline holding company
plunged.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Energy Service Co., a Houston energy services concern, led
the Amex; the company is facing delays in completing a $50
million hazardous-waste incinerator complex near Mobile,
Ariz. Varity Corp., a Toronto manufacturer of farm equipment
and auto parts, led the Big Board. Short selling of Varity
shares has been linked to a type of arbitrage involving the
company's preferred stock.
   Additionally, a closely watched indicator of negative
sentiment, the short interest ratio measured on the Big
Board, plunged at mid-June.
   New York exchange short interest climbed to 661,212,877
shares at June 15 from 644,549,698 shares at mid-May. On the
Amex, short interest edged up to 72,277,893 shares from an
adjusted 72,033,106.
   At mid-June 1989, short volume was 528,985,908 shares on
the Big Board, indicating a 25% increase, and 49,054,037
shares on the American exchange, indicating a 47% advance.
   Traders who sell short borrow stock and sell it, betting
that the stock's price will decline and that they can buy the
shares back later at a lower price for return to the lender.
   Short interest is the number of shares that haven't yet
been purchased for return to lenders. Although a substantial
short position reflects heavy speculation that a stock's
price will decline, some investors consider an increase in
short interest bullish because the borrowed shares eventually
must be bought back.
   Fluctuation in short interest of certain stocks also may
be caused partly by arbitraging. The figures occasionally
include incomplete transactions in restricted stock.
   The level of negative sentiment measured by the Big Board
short interest ratio sank to 3.86 from last month's 4.61. The
ratio is the number of trading days at the exchange's average
daily trading volume that would be required to convert the
total short interest position. Some analysts suggest,
however, that the ratio has weakened in value as an indicator
because options and other products can be used to hedge short
positions.
   Many investors in Varity have chosen to hold the company's
convertible preferred shares while shorting the common stock
to hedge their investment.
   Earlier this month, Varity said it will seek shareholder
approval for a plan to allow it to "pay inducements" in cash
or common shares to holders of preferred shares. The move,
aimed at reducing Varity's hefty preferred-share dividend
payments, ultimately could substantially pare the number of
preferred shares outstanding and reduce the short position in
the common.
   The American depositary receipts of Empresa Nacional De
Electricidad S.A. showed the largest short-volume increase on
the Big Board, climbing to 4,372,850 shares from 190,022.
Late last month, the Madrid utility said Spain's Ministry of
Industry and Energy wouldn't permit it to include $317
million of expenses relating to necessary repairs and
required modernization of the Vandellos I Nuclear Power Plant
in the base rate for electricity.
   Panhandle Eastern Corp., a Houston natural gas-pipeline
concern, saw short volume drop to 504,548 shares from
5,832,010, leading the Big Board decliners.
   Texas Air was the biggest volume decliner on the Amex,
with 4,570,106 shares compared with 8,547,761 a month
earlier.
   Fruit of the Loom Inc., a Chicago apparel concern, led the
Amex volume increases, rising to 4,357,279 shares from
2,896,033.
   The bellwether issue International Business Machines
Corp., the Armonk, N.Y., computer company, saw short interest
rise 22% to 4,908,645 shares, while closely watched New York
oil major Exxon Corp.'s volume eased 0.9% to 5,471,865 shares
from 5,519,394.
   The adjacent tables show the Big Board and Amex issues in
which a short interest position of at least 100,000 shares
existed at mid-June or in which the short position had
changed by at least 50,000 shares since mid-May (see
accompanying tables -- WSJ June 22, 1990).
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   CONTINENTAL AIRLINES HOLDINGS Inc. short interest volume
was 7,532,266 shares for the month ended June 15, making it
the largest-volume issue and bringing total American Stock
Exchange short volume to 75,240,053 shares. Because
Continental recently changed its name from Texas Air Corp.,
some brokerage firms neglected to report some of the
company's short positions, the Amex said.
   (WSJ June 25, 1990)
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   ENERGY SERVICE Co., a Houston energy services concern,
said the short interest in its shares for the month ended
June 15 rose because investors appear to be arbitraging its
common and preferred stock. The company was incorrectly
described in Friday's short interest article as being
involved in a hazardous-waste facility.
   (WSJ June 25, 1990)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
