<HL>
   Debt Ceiling Hit by Glitch
   In Accounting for Bonds
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- An unforeseen glitch in accounting for $30
billion of zero-coupon bonds sold this year to Mexico ensures
that the federal government's $3.12 trillion debt ceiling
will expire in early August.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady is expected to tell
congressional leaders that the ceiling must be raised in
early August. The debt cap had been expected to expire some
weeks later, but in any event, the Treasury needs a
debt-limit increase before Congress starts its August recess.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury's wiggle room was diminished by an immediate
addition of some $27 billion to the amount of debt subject to
the ceiling. That addition occurred when it was discovered
that the zero-coupon bonds sold by the Treasury to Mexico as
part of a debt-restructuring package don't qualify for a new
method of calculating zero-coupon bonds subject to the debt
ceiling. A Treasury spokesman said the department has
notified Capitol Hill of this development.
   The Treasury had been calculating the Mexico deal as
adding about $3 billion to the amount of debt subject to the
limit.
   The need to act on the debt bill before the August recess
could become a key pressure point for the current White
House-congressional budget summit. It also could cause
uncertainty in the financial markets regarding the Treasury's
August refunding, whose details are to be announced Aug. 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0063
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0063.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   House Panel
   Sets $15.8 Billion
   For Foreign Bill
   ----
   By David Rogers
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   FORGN LATAM FREST EUROP AFRIC
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The House Appropriations Committee approved
a $15.8 billion foreign operations bill for fiscal 1991 that
would cut U.S. military aid outside the Middle East and
impose new curbs on funds for El Salvador and non-Communist
forces in Cambodia.
   The measure reflects a temporary accord between the Bush
administration and the committee's Democratic leadership,
which agreed to soften cuts in foreign military aid in return
for Republican promises of support on the House floor.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Total foreign military assistance would fall to $4.63
billion in the budget year beginning Oct. 1, down 4% from
current levels but $144 million more than was proposed by a
House subcommittee last week. Limits on military aid to
Turkey and Greece would be relaxed, but Democrats succeeded
in preserving the thrust of their proposal to begin to roll
back arms expenditures and focus more on economic development
in a post-Cold War era.
   The committee trimmed some of its own initiatives in
development and economic programs, but aid to Eastern Europe
would still grow to almost $490 million, $189 million above
the administration's request. An estimated $800 million in
aid would be preserved to sub-Saharan Africa. And in
negotiations this week, the Treasury won a commitment of $50
million in new capital for the World Bank.
   Senior State Department and White House advisers
participated in negotiations over the bill, reflecting
concern in both the administration and Congress about
deteriorating support for foreign aid. The $15.8 billion
total would come on top of recent supplemental appropriations
for Panama and Nicaragua. When compared with the comparable
foreign operations bill last year, the measure would
represent a nearly 7% increase in aid and related
export-credit programs.
   The El Salvador and Cambodia provisions remain divisive,
and military aid to Turkey and Greece still would be cut by
almost 14%. Report language attached to the legislation is
sharply critical of the Turkish-backed government in northern
Cyprus, and taken as a whole, the readjustment in aid
represents a victory for the pro-Greece lobby.
   In the case of El Salvador, 50% of future military aid
would be withheld in line with a House vote this spring.
   And while spending would be continued for the
non-Communist resistance fighters in Cambodia, restrictions
attached yesterday were written so broadly that they
effectively would bar aid for military operations directly or
indirectly supportive of the anti-government Khmer Rouge.
   The $50 million in new capital for the World Bank is less
than half of what the Treasury Department requested. And
while the bill would provide $70 million sought by the
administration for the new European Development Bank,
restrictions were attached in an effort to put leverage on
Western governments -- particularly West Germany -- to
forgive Poland's immense debt.
   Apart from the foreign operations bill, U.S. contributions
to the United Nations and affiliated health and nutrition
organizations would increase significantly under a separate
$10.5 billion fiscal 1991 measure pending before the full
House. Contributions to international organizations generally
would grow by 28% to an estimated $787.6 million, and $115
million would be provided for peacekeeping organizations -- a
41% increase from fiscal 1990.
   The same bill would provide for an expanded State
Department budget for the new fiscal year. It is accompanied
by a report that touches on the continued conflict in
Afghanistan and U.S. representation in Kabul. When Soviet
troops withdrew from Afghanistan more than a year ago,
Washington withdrew its personnel from the U.S. Embassy in
the capital. Report language inserted by Rep. Silvio Conte of
Massachusetts, the ranking Republican on the House
Appropriations Committee, calls for a review of this policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0062
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0062.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dividend News:
   Syntech to Omit
   Preferred Dividend
   Sixth Time in a Row
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   SYNE
</CO>
<IN>
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<LP>
   RENO, Nev. -- Syntech International Inc. said it will miss
a sixth consecutive dividend payment on its preferred stock,
and may have to seek bankruptcy-court protection if it fails
to win restructuring of two existing lottery contracts.
   Loss-plagued Syntech is one of a handful of makers of
transaction-processing equipment used in state-supported
lotteries. The company said omitting of the preferred
dividend triggers provisions in its certificate of
incorporation that allows preferred holders as a class to
select two members on the company's four-member board.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Syntech couldn't be reached for comment on whether those
holders had yet demanded those seats.
   Syntech said it omitted the latest payout, due in
September, because of its deteriorating financial condition.
The company said its "ability to continue as a going concern
and remain in existence" hinges upon restructuring of the two
lottery contracts. It provided no details about the
contracts.
   "If such new arrangements cannot be worked out promptly
the company will have no alternative but to consider seeking
relief" under Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code,
Thomas A. McChristy, Syntech's chief executive, said in a
news release. Under Chapter 11, a company seeks protection
from its creditors while working out a plan to pay its debt.
   Syntech posted a loss in fiscal 1989 ended Sept. 30 of
$15.1 million, or $2.78 a share, on revenue of $11.3 million.
In the first quarter ended Dec. 31, the company had a loss of
$2.1 million, or 40 cents a share, on revenue of $6.6
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
