<HL>
   General Binding Sees
   Profit Falling Below
   Analysts' Forecasts
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   GBND
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NORTHBROOK, Ill. -- General Binding Corp., hurt by "soft"
markets and higher expenses, said it expects second quarter
earnings to fall short of analysts' expectations.
   Rudolph Grua, president and chief executive officer, said
the office products company expects to report profit fell to
30 cents or 31 cents a share from 35 cents a year earlier. He
said that would put net income at $4.8 million to $5 million,
down from $5.6 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Grua said analysts and the company had projected
earnings around 38 cents a share. He said higher expenses,
along with slower sales growth in May and June, forced the
lowering.
   In addition, Mr. Grua said soft markets mean flat gross
margins in its basic business of making machines and supplies
to laminate and bind paper. And he said margins are down in
the company's three-ring metal binder business.
   The news sent General Binding shares down $2.50 to close
at $18.50 in over-the-counter trading yesterday.
   The expected earnings would mark the second consecutive
quarterly shortfall for General Binding after a 16-quarter
string of higher earnings.
   But Mr. Grua said he expects that modestly higher earnings
in this year's final two quarters should help the company
meet or slightly exceed $18.8 million, or $1.18 a share,
which the company reported last year before an income tax
refund made net $20.1 million, or $1.26 a share.
   General Binding expects second quarter sales to increase
about 11% to $80 million from $71.9 million a year earlier.
But excluding the Loose Leaf Metals unit acquired last
August, comparable sales are expected to rise about 9% --
below the company's earlier expectation of double-digit
growth.
   Mr. Grua attributed the lower-than-expected sales to
softer international markets for office products. The sales
shortfall is mainly on the machine side, Mr. Grua said. He
said the company's sales of supplies for those machines
remain healthy.
   Despite the earnings setback, Mr. Grua said he doesn't
plan to stop looking for acquisitions or interrupt the
company's annual dividend increases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0056
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0056.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Bush Deficit Plan
   Leaves Democrats
   Split on Next Step
   ----
   By David Wessel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Democrats continued to grouse about the Bush
administration's new $51-billion deficit-reduction plan, but
they didn't walk away from budget talks with the White House.
   While uniformly critical of the plan, Democrats appeared
split on how to proceed. Senate Budget Committee Chairman
James Sasser (D., Tenn.) complained the new plan "doesn't
give us any foundation on which to build." But his House
counterpart, Rep. Leon Panetta (D., Calif.), deemed it "a
starting point" that ought to lead to more give-and-take at
the White House-Congress budget summit. Democrats plan to
huddle on strategy this weekend before rejoining the talks
Monday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The administration says its new blueprint would shrink the
projected fiscal 1991 deficit by $50.7 billion. That isn't
nearly enough to avoid across-the-board spending cuts under
the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law. The new proposal
includes $11.7 billion in spending cuts in addition to ones
President Bush proposed in January.
   President Bush told reporters he is ready to allow the
automatic budget cuts required by law to go into effect if an
agreement isn't signed. He also said he expects interest
rates to decline if a budget agreement is signed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0055
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0055.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Grumman, Boeing
   Settle Cost Dispute
   On Defense Program
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   GQ BA
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   BETHPAGE, N.Y. -- Grumman Corp. and Boeing Co. said they
settled their dispute over costs for the U.S. defense program
called Joint Stars.
   "The settlement eliminates substantial claims by both
parties concerning responsibility for the costs of completion
of the first two Joint Stars aircraft," the companies said. A
Grumman spokesman said no details of the settlement would be
released.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a joint statement, Grumman Chairman John O'Brien and
Boeing Vice Chairman Malcolm Stamper said, "This settlement
will improve our mutual concentration on other important
assignments on which we are working together."
   In 1985, Grumman won a $657 million contract for a
five-year development program for the Joint Surveillance
Target Attack Radar System, which will identify ground
targets and guide aircraft and missiles. The value of the
contract has since been increased to $850 million, Grumman
said.
   Meanwhile, Boeing won an $80.2 million subcontract to
modify two aircraft for the radar system's "aerial platform,"
but late in 1987 Boeing requested a $122.5 million price
increase. Boeing alleged that Grumman's demands on the
subcontractor had departed from the contract and driven up
costs.
   For its part, Grumman then sought an undisclosed sum from
Boeing "for damages caused by deficiencies in performance of
the subcontract."
   Grumman said Joint Stars is "in the final phases" of
flight testing by Grumman, with a U.S. Air Force evaluation
planned for this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
