<HL>
   Enterprise -- Financing Small Business:
   Big Venture Funds Grow; Securities Rule Holds Promise
   ----
   By Udayan Gupta
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
INSURANCE (INS)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<GV>
INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE (IRS)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   BIG VENTURE CAPITAL partnerships grow while others find
pickings lean.
   New Enterprise Associates, which already manages $470
million in venture capital funds, last week raised another
$200 million from such investors as Chicago's Brinson
Partners and the pension fund of American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co. And Canaan Partners, Rowayton, Conn., raised
$200 million this month to add to the $240 million it already
manages.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The venture partnerships mostly are "getting their money
from pension funds who want to have a small portion of their
assets in venture capital," says a San Francisco
institutional investor. "The pension funds are playing it
safe by going with the large ones."
   But the big funds also have been able to separate
themselves from others with specific strategies. New
Enterprise, for example, has adopted a national investment
strategy, establishing a network of regional and
industry-specific "feeder funds" to provide candidates for
investment, says Richard Kramlich, a New Enterprise managing
partner. Canaan is focusing on providing capital for
expansion and acquisitions of small companies.
   Still, most funds formed in the '80s will face an uphill
struggle raising new money, investors say. "Their prior funds
haven't fulfilled their promise," says Anthony Hoberman, head
of venture capital investing for Alliance Capital Management
Inc.
   Only a handful of recent deals have produced returns
comparable with a Genentech or Apple Computer, he adds.
   ---
   A RECENT SECURITIES rule could give small firms a new way
to raise money.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission's 144a rule, which
was approved in April, could allow small entrepreneurial
companies to raise capital cheaply and effectively, says
attorney Joseph Bartlett, partner in Gaston &amp; Snow, New York.
   Under the rule, institutions with investments of $100
million or more can buy and sell previously restricted,
privately placed stocks and bonds. In effect, more investors
could be interested in the restricted shares of small firms
because they could be traded more easily. Restricted shares
have restrictions on trading, commonly delimiting the
category of buyers or the minimum period the stock must be
held.
   Mr. Bartlett and others think that small companies,
especially those that already have some revenues or are
profitable, could significantly benefit from the rule. "It
would allow them to sell stock cheaper and faster and perhaps
with less potential liability," he says. The liability risk
in issuing these stocks is reduced because the buyers are
so-called sophisticated investors, he notes.
   These investors include pension funds, insurance companies
and banks -- concerns that traditionally have acquired stock
in closely held businesses through venture capital pools but
increasingly want to buy stock directly. Still, for the rule
to really have an impact on closely held concerns, investment
bankers will have to make a market in the 144a stock. That
means they must put up their own capital to provide a trading
market, says Mr. Bartlett.
   The test for 144a for smaller entrepreneurial firms will
be whether there are enough qualified institutional investors
willing to buy and sell these shares, says Edward Smith,
managing director of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   ---
   KEY INVESTMENTS in computer-related businesses slip.
   Venture capital placed in computer-related businesses
declined 38% in the first quarter of 1990 to the lowest
quarterly total in five years, says Technologic Computer
Letter, an industry newsletter in New York. Such capital is a
major source of funding for new technology concerns.
   Only $225 million went to computer-related venture deals
in the first quarter of 1990, compared with $362 million a
year earlier, the newsletter notes. The decline follows a
year in which investments in computer ventures were flat.
Computer-related ventures received $1.24 billion in 1989,
compared with $1.26 billion in 1988.
   Entrepreneurs aren't successfully exploiting new
technology ideas, venture capitalists contend. "There's only
been a small increase in new concepts. Most entrepreneurs
keep churning out the same old ideas," complains Westport,
Conn., venture capitalist Stewart Greenfield.
   "Venture capitalists aren't seeing the deals or the
quality of deals they like," says Richard Shaffer, editor of
Technologic. And having been burnt by over-competition in
areas such as disk drives, computer systems and personal
computers, "they're resisting the me-too company," adds Mr.
Shaffer.
   Nonetheless, some venture capitalists believe the decline
could have some benefits for entrepreneurs. "The few
companies that do get money now will get more money and
attention," promises one East Coast venture capitalist.
   ---
   AN IRS VICTORY in a real estate partnership case troubles
venture capitalists.
   A U.S. tax court recently ruled that an individual who
receives a "carried interest" in a partnership is required to
pay taxes on projected profits at the time he receives that
interest rather than when he actually pockets the gains. Many
investment partnerships grant a carried interest -- an
interest that the partner doesn't pay for -- to help
compensate partners who manage the program. The tax court
decision could affect partnerships beyond the real estate
field, tax attorneys say.
   Most experienced tax lawyers previously believed that
there was little risk of a general partner's owing taxes on
profits that haven't been earned, says attorney James Dreyfus
of Fulbright Jaworski &amp; Reavis McGrath, New York.
   Even though a 1974 court case established a precedent for
collecting taxes on projected carried-interest profits, the
Internal Revenue Service had never attempted to apply it.
   "If they begin to enforce the {new} ruling, it will take a
lot of the financial incentive out of forming such
partnerships," Mr. Dreyfus says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0051
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0051.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Brokerage Firms
   Slam Wall Street's
   `Soft-Dollar' Deals
   ----
   By Kevin G. Salwen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   MS LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Two major Wall Street firms fired a missile
at a prevalent institutional stock- and bond-trading
practice, asking federal officials to curtail sharply the way
pension funds direct their transactions.
   The letter, from Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. and Morgan Stanley
Group Inc. to Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole, takes on a
lifeblood of Wall Street -- "soft dollars." A barter form of
payment, soft dollars are credits that pension funds and
mutual funds receive from brokerage firms for trading
commissions. The funds use those credits instead of cash to
pay for such things as research, computer services,
economists and client referrals.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Backers say they help institutions pick and choose the
services they want and allow star Wall Street analysts to
form their own boutique firms. But critics counter that the
soft-dollar business is a quagmire, rife with fraud that
forces pensioners to pay for services that fund managers
should be paying themselves. Moreover, Goldman and Morgan
contend that soft dollars hurt overall market liquidity and
create excess volatility.
   The letter from the two firms points up Wall Street's rift
over the soft-dollar question. Most other brokerages have
reluctantly set up their own soft-dollar units on the
assumption that failing to do so would force business to
other firms. Morgan and Goldman have steadfastly refused to
enter the fray, and now appear to be hoping for regulatory
relief.
   The debate over soft dollars has heated up again in the
past few years as volume since the October 1987 stock-market
crash has remained at sharply lower levels than during the
mid-1980s. Because large institutions, such as mutual funds
and pension funds, have to reimburse soft-dollar brokers for
services no matter how much volume they do, Wall Street firms
without soft-dollar operations are getting a proportionately
smaller share of the pie.
   The two firms asked the Labor Department and the
Securities and Exchange Commission to: require pension plans
to disclose the extent of soft-dollar deals; clarify the
types of soft-dollar accords that fall outside pension rules;
and then take enforcement action.
   The soft-dollar issue isn't likely to fade soon. "This
goes to the very heart of what's going on on Wall Street,"
said Lee Pickard, a Washington lawyer who represents many
soft-dollar firms. "It's a competitive turf battle."
   The letter and an accompanying report, copies of which
were obtained by this newspaper, were sent several months ago
by Robert Rubin, Goldman's vice chairman, and Richard Fisher,
Morgan Stanley's president. A Morgan Stanley spokeswoman said
the Labor Department hasn't formally responded. She said that
the letter was a follow-up to an SEC roundtable held last
year on soft dollars, and that Morgan Stanley wanted to
express concern about the use of soft-dollar accords in
fixed-income investing. Goldman Sachs declined to comment.
   "It's an area we have been interested in for a number of
years and an area we continue to have interest in," said
Charles Lerner, director of enforcement at the Labor
Department's Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration. He
declined to say what the agency might do.
   But the reception from the SEC doesn't appear to be
particularly warm. Robert Colby, chief counsel for market
regulation, said the agency has taken a wait-and-see attitude
toward changing the rules on soft dollars. "There's no
timetable for deciding when to move on any of these
complaints," he said.
   "Obviously for these firms there are competitive concerns
that mingle with altruism and their concerns for the
clients," Mr. Colby said. "That really calls for caution."
   Goldman and Morgan contend in their report that soft
dollars are a major problem for the markets. They estimate
that 30% to 50% of the total trades on the New York Stock
Exchange use soft dollars.
   "The overall consequence of soft-dollar practices on the
securities markets is a decrease in market liquidity, which
can lead to increased market volatility and general
disruption of trading," the report said. Moreover, soft
dollars are hurting the return that pension funds are getting
"because investment managers are not obtaining best execution
of securities trades in transactions involving soft dollars."
   At the heart of the firms' argument is a securities-law
provision called Section 28e, which allows money managers to
use soft-dollar practices if they receive research in return.
If the arrangement meets Section 28e guidelines, practices
that otherwise would violate Employee Retirement Income
Security Act laws are protected from Labor Department
enforcement action.
   But Morgan and Goldman said that pension-plan sponsors
aren't being told how soft dollars are being used. Moreover,
they added that some soft dollars are being used for futures
transactions, in violation of Section 28e, which covers only
securities trades.
   Some soft-dollar firms argue that Goldman and Morgan are
simply engaged in a misguided campaign of sour grapes. "It's
an attempt to restrict competition by lobbying the
regulators," said Don Potts, president of Capital
Institutional Services Inc., a large independent soft-dollar
firm based in Dallas. "The real problem we're dealing with
here is the overcapacity of Wall Street."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0050
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0050.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Industrials Gain 6.43 on Late Rally;
   End-of-Quarter Buying Is Factor
   ----
   By David Wilson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Stock prices closed higher on the strength of
a late rally, attributed to end-of-quarter buying by
institutions and futures-related buy programs. Trading was
subdued.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average, which spent most of the
session drifting at lower levels, moved back above the 2900
level by gaining 6.43 to 2901.73.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Today represents the end of the second quarter for many
money managers. Under normal procedures, any trades made
today would be settled next Friday, the final session of the
quarter.
   Analysts cited "window dressing," or last-minute
adjustments that institutions make with an eye toward
presenting the best possible quarterly reports to clients, as
a major factor fueling the market's late recovery.
   Buy programs tied to stock-index arbitrage, in which
traders purchase baskets of stocks and sell index-futures
contracts in order to profit from the price differential
between them, also surfaced near the close to give stocks a
boost.
   The arbitrage buying helped offset earlier waves of sell
programs, which had knocked back the market at the opening
and again at midday. The industrial average hit bottom with a
loss of about 20 points.
   Trading activity has been sluggish all week, and the
latest session continued that pattern. Some 138,570,000
shares changed hands on the New York Stock Exchange, compared
with 137,420,000 Wednesday.
   Advancing issues led decliners on the Big Board by 774 to
696. Standard &amp; Poor's 500-Stock Index rose 1.37 to 360.47,
the New York Stock Exchange Composite Index gained 0.65 to
196.49 and the Dow Jones Equity Market Index went up 1.11 to
335.33.
   The Big Board's list of most active issues included a
number of stocks that have recently been under pressure,
including:
   -- United Telecommunications, which dropped 1/4 to 39 in
Big Board composite trading of 1.5 million shares. The stock
moved lower last week after PaineWebber reduced its earnings
estimates for the second quarter and 1990.
   Its latest fall took place as American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph put a price plan into effect that allows it to
offer special rates to individual customers in response to a
competing proposal by another carrier. AT&amp;T rose 1/2 to 43
5/8.
   -- Occidental Petroleum, which rose 1/8 to 25 7/8 on 1.3
million shares after trading as low as 25 1/4 during the
session. Standard &amp; Poor's downgraded its ratings on the
company's debt earlier this week.
   -- Limited Inc., which slid 5/8 to 22 3/4 on 1.1 million
shares. Retail sales have fallen in each of the past three
months, and apparel sales have been especially sluggish,
sparking concern about earnings prospects for those
companies.
   Another issue to slide in active trading was Du Pont,
which said it has allocated funds for the design of four
plants that would produce alternatives to
chlorofluorocarbons. The stock fell 1 to 38 1/8 on 1.1
million shares. Du Pont said it expects to spend more than $1
billion to develop and produce the alternatives, including
$240 million already invested and additional projected costs
over the next 10 years.
   American Cyanamid rose 1 1/4 to 57 1/8 after agreeing to
sell the household-products business of its Shulton unit to
Clorox for $465 million. Analysts told Dow Jones Professional
Investor Report they expect Cyanamid to use the sale proceeds
mainly to buy back common stock; Leonard Bogner of
Prudential-Bache Securities estimated that the company would
purchase about five million of its 94.4 million shares
outstanding.
   A spokeswoman for Cyanamid acknowledged that the company
is considering a buy-back, but added that it hasn't yet made
a decision to proceed. Clorox tumbled 1 3/4 to 42 1/8; the
company estimated that the acquisition would dilute its
earnings by 30 cents to 40 cents a share in the first year
and 10 cents a share in the second year.
   Johnson &amp; Johnson advanced 2 to 66 5/8 after the Food and
Drug Administration approved the use of Levamisole, a drug
made by the company's Janssen Research Foundation to treat
advanced cases of colon cancer in combination with another
drug. Separately, Dean Witter Reynolds increased its
estimates of the company's 1990 and 1991 earnings.
   Upjohn, which climbed two points Wednesday on takeover
speculation, eased 1/4 to 41 7/8 as 1.5 million shares were
traded. Schering-Plough and American Home Products had been
mentioned as possible suitors; both declined to comment, as
did Upjohn.
   Equifax, which agreed to acquire Telecredit in a stock
swap, tumbled 2 5/8 to 19 1/2. The company will exchange 2.69
of its common shares for each Telecredit share.
   Delta Air Lines fell 1 1/4 to 75 3/4. Wertheim Schroder
lowered its investment rating on the stock, along with its
earnings estimates for the company's fiscal fourth quarter,
ending this month, and calendar 1990. Analyst Candace
Browning said lower-than-expected domestic air traffic will
affect its results.
   VF retreated 2 1/4 to 25 following its forecast that
second-quarter earnings per share would be about 47% lower
than a year earlier, when it posted net income of 67 cents a
share.
   Molecular Biosystems dropped 5/8 to 18 3/4. The company
said it expects to report earnings between 20 cents and 25
cents a share for the fiscal year ending next March, well
below most analysts' projections, as it emphasizes growth
over profits.
   Caterpillar dropped 7/8 to 64 1/4 after Prudential-Bache
lowered its investment rating and 1990 earnings estimate,
citing weak orders for the company's large machines in May.
   CPC International went up 1 1/2 to 80 1/4 and set a new
52-week high by peaking at 80 1/2. Michael Metz, a market
strategist at Oppenheimer &amp; Co., told the investor report he
recommended the stock and said it "acts like it's under
accumulation" by a major corporate buyer.
   Liggett Group added 5/8 to 11 3/4. The company said it
plans to restructure its tobacco and sports-marketing units
as separate companies and said it may repurchase as many as
one million of its common shares.
   WMS Industries climbed 1 1/8 to 9 1/2. Newsletter writer
Charles LaLoggia commented favorably about WMS in a
television interview; he told the investor report it is
"reasonable" to consider the company as a possible takeover
target for Viacom. Sumner N. Redstone, Viacom's chairman,
holds a 28.9% stake in WMS.
   Vishay Intertechnology declined 7/8 to 21 3/8. The
company, which has about 12.4 million common and Class B
shares outstanding, said it is considering a public offering
of two million common shares.
   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index dropped
0.59 to 360.22. Volume totaled 10,550,000 shares.
   AT&amp;E rose 1 1/8 to 22 5/8. Bell Atlantic disclosed that it
had accumulated a stake in the company and plans to purchase
additional shares; it declined to provide the size of its
holding.
   Bolar Pharmaceutical, which said a lawsuit filed last week
by SmithKline Beecham would have a "material adverse effect"
on the company if the British-based firm wins the case, fell
3/4 to 5 7/8. The suit charges Bolar with fraud in obtaining
federal approval for a generic version of Dyazide,
SmithKline's blood-pressure drug.
</TEXT>
