<HL>
   Business Brief -- First Bank System Inc.:
   Pact to Buy Banks of Iowa
   Ended by Minneapolis Firm
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   BIOW FBS
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   First Bank System Inc., Minneapolis, said it ended a
nearly nine-year old agreement to acquire Banks of Iowa Inc.
and plans to sell back to the Des Moines banking concern
550,197 Class B nonvoting shares for about $38 million, or
$69 a share.
   The 1981 agreement called for First Bank to acquire Banks
of Iowa for at least 1.5 times its shareholders equity, when
permitted by Iowa banking law, which at the time didn't allow
interstate acquisitions.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Both companies have gone through some big changes since
then, however. First, the depressed farm economy battered
nearly all Iowa banks. And more recently, First Bank itself
was hurt by some big bond and loan losses.
   Interstate banking powers come to Iowa Jan. 1, and Banks
of Iowa said it plans to seek another buyer. With about $2.6
billion in assets and shareholders equity of $214 million at
March 31, it is the biggest bankholding company based in
Iowa.
   Banks of Iowa common stock closed at $69.50, down 50
cents, in over-the-counter trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900622-0012
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900622-0012.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Abitibi-Price Inc.:
   De-Inking Plant to Be Built
   At Alabama Newsprint Mill
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   ABY
</CO>
<LP>
   Abitibi-Price Inc., a Toronto-based forest products
concern, said it plans to build a US$56 million de-inking
plant at its 50%-owned newsprint mill in Claiborne, Ala.
   Abitibi-Price, 82%-owned by the Reichmann family's closely
held Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd., said the plant will
process 125,000 metric tons of wastepaper annually. The
newsprint mill has an annual capacity of 220,000 metric tons
and is scheduled to begin operations next month. A metric ton
is equal to about 2,204.62 pounds.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Claiborne newsprint mill, Alabama River Newsprint Co.,
is jointly owned by Abitibi-Price and Parsons &amp; Whittemore
Inc. of New York, a woodpulp maker and builder of pulp and
paper mills. By the end of next year, newsprint made at the
mill will contain as much as 40% recycled paper,
Abitibi-Price said.
   Construction of the de-inking plant, which could begin
next month, is subject to completion of financing agreements
with Alabama River Newsprint's creditors. The Alabama State
Teachers' Retirement Fund agreed in principle to lend US$15
million to the project, Abitibi-Price said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
