<HL>
   U.S. Auto Makers
   Expect 3.1% Boost
   In Output This Week
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   C F GM HMC TOYOY NSANY J.MZD SBRU J.IZM J.MOT
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- The 10 major U.S. auto makers planned to build
145,014 cars this week, a 3.1% increase from 140,592 cars
built a year ago.
   Domestic auto makers said all plants are scheduled to
operate next week, with several working overtime.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said it plans overtime at its
assembly plants in Janesville, Wis., and Lansing, Mich. GM
said its Arlington, Texas, assembly plant reopens June 27. It
was idled April 27 to re-tool for the 1991 Chevrolet Caprice
and Cadillac Brougham.
   Ford Motor Co. scheduled daily and weekend overtime at
production facilities in Wayne, Mich., Wixom, Mich., and
Louisville, Ky. Ford said all of its truck plants are to work
overtime next week.
   Chrysler Corp. said it plans daily and weekend overtime at
its assembly plants in Sterling Heights, Mich., St. Louis,
Mo., Belvidere, Ill., and Newark, Del.
