<HL>
   Credit Ratings:
   Moody's Lowers
   Debt Ratings
   Of Centel Corp.
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17
</SO>
<CO>
   CNT
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Moody's Investors Service, citing Centel
Corp.'s "aggressive expansion of its cellular operations,"
lowered its ratings on about $1.2 billion in debt issued by
the telecommunications concern and two subsidiaries.
   The rating concern said the "capital expenditure
requirements, external financing burden, and earnings
pressure" accompanying Centel's cellular-telephone expansion
strategy will result in "increased business risk and debt
protection measures."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Moody's added, however, that it thinks the cellular
telephone business "can provide Centel with considerable cash
flow and profit potential over the longer term."
   Centel's first mortgage bonds, debentures and notes were
marked down to Baa-3 from Baa-1; its commercial paper rating
was reduced to Prime-3 from Prime-2.
   The company's Centel Capital unit had ratings on its
debentures and notes reduced to Baa-3 from Baa-1, and its
commercial paper was lowered to Prime-3 from Prime-2.
   Ratings on the company's Central Telephone Co.'s first
mortgage bonds were lowered to single-A-1 from double-A-2,
and its debentures reduced to single-A-2 from double-A-3.
Moody's said Central Telephone is entering a series of
regulatory hearings that may result in soft earnings
performance in the "intermediate term."
   A Centel spokesman said the company is "disappointed" with
Moody's move. "We remain very optimistic about cellular and
its long-term potential," and will continue the expansion
effort, he said. The spokesman specifically disagreed with
Moody's markdown of the company's commercial paper, saying
that Centel's "short-term liquidity situation is strong,"
particularly after it recently boosted a revolving credit
agreement with lenders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
